<h2><a name=3D"SECTION00031000000000000000">
Runge-Kutta Methods</a>
</h2>=20
In the forward Euler method, we used the information on the slope or the de=
rivative of <i>y</i>=20
at the given time step to extrapolate the solution to the next time-step. T=
he LTE for the=20
method is O(<i>h</i><sup>2</sup>), resulting in a first order numerical tec=
hnique. Runge-Kutta methods=20
are a class of methods which judiciously uses the information on the 'slope=
' at more than one point=20
to extrapolate the solution to the future time step. Let's discuss first th=
e derivation of=20
the <em>second</em> order RK method where the LTE is O(<i>h</i><sup>3</sup>=
). =20

<p>
Given the IVP of Eq. 6, and a time step <i>h</i>, and the solution <i>y</i>=
<sub><i>n</i></sub> at the <i>n</i>th time step,=20
let's say that we wish to compute <i>y</i><sub><i>n</i>+1</sub> in the foll=
owing fashion:
<br>
</p><div align=3D"CENTER">

<!-- MATH: \begin{eqnarray}
&& k_1 =3D hf(y_n,t_n)\nonumber \\
&& k_2 =3D hf(y_n+\beta k_1, t_n + \alpha h) \nonumber \\
&& y_{n+1} =3D y_n + ak_1 + bk_2,
\end{eqnarray} -->

