rential_Equations_Notes/img33.gif" alt=3D"$\displaystyle k_2 =3D hf(y_n+\be=
ta k_1, t_n + \alpha h)$"></td>
<td width=3D"10" align=3D"RIGHT">
&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr valign=3D"MIDDLE"><td nowrap=3D"" align=3D"RIGHT">&nbsp;</td>
<td>&nbsp;</td>
<td align=3D"LEFT" nowrap=3D""><i>y</i><sub><i>n</i>+1</sub> =3D <i>y</i><s=
ub><i>n</i></sub> + <i>ak</i><sub>1</sub> + <i>bk</i><sub>2</sub>,</td>
<td width=3D"10" align=3D"RIGHT">
(12)</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
<br clear=3D"ALL"><p></p>
where the constants <img width=3D"17" height=3D"17" align=3D"BOTTOM" border=
=3D"0" src=3D"https://web.mit.edu/10.001/Web/Course_Notes/Differential_Equa=
tions_Notes/img34.gif" alt=3D"$\alpha$">,
<img width=3D"16" height=3D"34" align=3D"MIDDLE" border=3D"0" src=3D"https:=
//web.mit.edu/10.001/Web/Course_Notes/Differential_Equations_Notes/img35.gi=
f" alt=3D"$\beta$">,
<i>a</i> and <i>b</i> have to be evaluated so that <em>the=20
resulting method has a LTE O(</em><i>h</i><sup>3</sup><em>)</em>. Note that=
 if <i>k</i><sub>2</sub>=3D0 and <i>a</i>=3D1, then Eq. 13 reduces=20
to the forward Euler method. =20

<p>
Now, let's write down the Taylor series expansion of <i>y</i> in the neighb=
orhood of <i>t</i><sub><i>n</i></sub> correct to=20
the <i>h</i><sup>2</sup> term i.e.,=20
<br></p><p></p>
<div align=3D"CENTER">

<!-- MATH: \begin{equation}
y(t_{n+1}) =3D y(t_n) + h \frac{dy}{dt}|_{t_n} + \frac {h^2}{2} \frac{d^2y}=
{dt^2}|_{t_n}  + {\mbox{O}}(h^3).
\end{equation} -->

